  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What does "mental health parity" actually mean?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">It means BUPA treats mental health claims the same as physical health claims. No separate caps, no visit limits, no waiting periods beyond the standard policy terms. If your plan covers unlimited physical therapy visits, it covers unlimited therapy sessions. Most insurers cap mental health at 20-30 visits annually.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is the maternity waiting period so long (18 months)?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">BUPA's 18-month maternity wait is the longest in the market (Cigna is 12 months, Allianz is 10 months). This prevents people from enrolling just for pregnancy coverage. If you're planning to have a baby within 18 months, consider a competitor with a shorter waiting period.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does BUPA handle pre-existing conditions?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">BUPA uses individual medical underwriting rather than blanket exclusions. They assess your specific health history and may cover conditions that other insurers exclude. However, some conditions may still be excluded or have waiting periods. You'll know what's covered before you commit.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is BUPA worth the higher price?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">It depends on your needs. If you need comprehensive mental health coverage, BUPA's parity model can save thousands compared to capped competitors. If you're healthy with no mental health needs, you're paying premium for a feature you won't use—Cigna or Allianz may offer better value.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What does "no shareholders" mean for me?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">BUPA reinvests profits into healthcare services rather than paying dividends to shareholders. This removes the pressure to deny claims or cut costs to boost stock price. It's not a guarantee of better service, but it aligns BUPA's incentives more closely with member outcomes.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does BUPA cover ADHD and addiction treatment?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. BUPA covers ADHD assessment and ongoing treatment (medication, psychiatry) as well as addiction/rehabilitation programs. These are commonly excluded by other insurers. This coverage alone can justify the premium for those who need it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>BUPA Global is the clear choice for expats who prioritize mental health coverage.</strong> Mental health parity, ADHD coverage, addiction treatment, and no visit limits make it the gold standard for comprehensive mental healthcare. The no-shareholder structure and 75-year track record add stability.
  </p>
  <p>
    However, BUPA's premium pricing means it's not for everyone. If you're healthy, don't anticipate mental health needs, or are budget-conscious, you'll likely find better value with Cigna Global or Allianz Care. And the 18-month maternity waiting period is a dealbreaker for family planning.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bottom line:</strong> For mental health, BUPA is unmatched. For everyone else, shop around and compare the premium against your actual needs.
  </p>

